At your command. Ready to follow your every move, the MRAD adapts to a variety of user needs without sacrificing performance. With unrelenting precision and unfailing accuracy, this bolt action newcomer has  already defined a whole new class of long-range rifles. 

The MRAD rifle’s user-changeable barrel system is just one example of this hardworking gun’s modularity. The precision-grade barrel can be removed by simply unscrewing two bolts using a  

standard Torx wrench. Besides reducing maintenance and logistical burdens, this unique design paves the way for future caliber interchangeability and serviceability. 

The MRAD also boasts Barrett’s new easily accessed trigger module. This match-grade trigger is drop-fire-proof and combat-ready. The thumb-operated safety can be configured for left or right hand operation. The ambidextrous magazine release can be used intuitively while retaining a firing grip and cheek weld. 

Integrated into the MRAD rifle’s 7000 series aluminum upper receiver is an M1913 rail with 30 MOA taper and 21.75 inches of rail space. The configurable side and bottom rails can also hold a number of accessories. 

The MRAD rifle’s stock is foldable for enhanced portability yet locks in as solid as a fixed-stock rifle, creating a rigid platform for consistent firing. When folded, the stock latches around the bolt handle for added security during transport. Because the stock folds to the bolt handle side of the action, the rifle is the same width overall, folded or extended. 

Made of a temperature-resistant polymer, the adjustable cheek piece also offers a consistent rifle-to-user contact point. The rifle’s length of pull can be set to five different positions with the push of a single button. 

From its quick-detach sling mounts to the Barrett Multi-Role Brown color of the rifle that blends into any environment—every detail of the MRAD has been carefully designed to create one thing: a high-performance rifle you can truly make your own.

Very fine condition, WWII Nazi German marked Polish Radom VZ-35 pistol in 9mm. This good looking gun was made under Nazi occupation and has all matching numbers and a beautiful original finish. Pistol is serial number A6610 with matching numbers on the frame, barrel and inside the slide. Gun is Not import marked and has 2 eagle 77 proofs and a WaA 623 waffenampt on the slide that are clearly shown. Metal finish is a beautiful original blue with just a little holster wear. Correct original grips have the Polish VIS logo on each side and no cracks or chips. Pommel has lanyard loop, bore is fine and bright with strong rifling. Correct wartime mag has a Nazi proof on the base. Action is tight and functions fine. A scarce WWII Nazi German use pistol with nice markings and matching numbers.

title: For Sale:  M91/30 Mosin Nagan with 880 rounds of ammo

A M91/30 Mosin Nagan that was assembled in the arsenal at Izhevsk (Soviet Union). She is marked 1937 and originally started out with a Serial Number 4538. She’s been renumbered with an R0XXXXX Number, and identified as a RUSS 762X54 M91/30. She’s covered with various proof marks and cartouches that tell a lot.

After WWII she probably took a trip to the Balkans and got refinished. After that she was covered in Cosmoline and sat out things to the end of the Cold War.

It looks unissued and unfired (all though I can't say for sure). The furniture is in excellent shape. It is a wonderful example of this fine weapon.

Included: bayonet, cleaning rod, cleaning kit, oil can, sling, ammo pouch and and 880 rounds of 7.62x54. There is a thin layer of Cosmoline remaining.

title: For Sale:  M14  M1A  Springfield Armory Factory FIVE (5) round Magazines & Springfield Armory factory Cleaning kit.
postcontent:
Sold the gun years ago.
Will ship lower 48 states were legal
$13.95 USPS priority mail

2 Five (5) round steel Magazines & Springfield Armory M1A cleaning kit package = $80
One is a true 5 round, and the other is a 10 round with a block in it for 5 rounds. 
These Magazines were produced by CMI(Check-Mate Industries) for Springfield Armory
The magazine followers were produced by Borg Warner & Winchester Olin-Matheson

Springfield Armory cleaning kit package does not have a case.

Local Gun shop purchased all the rest of the magazines I had a few months back and sold them for $65-85 each.  They were new unused 20/10/5 rounders.  Found these last two cleaning out some hunting gear.   Used one deer season back in the 90s.   Back in the 90s Springfield armory did not stamp their logo on the magazines.   The way to determine Manufacturer if not initialed is by USGI Drawing D7790197 which allows for the latch plate to be attached to the magazine body by two, four, five or six welds. USGI M14 magazine latch plate weld dimple patterns were consistently the same pattern according to manufacturer.  The following latch plate dimple pattern was consistently used for genuine USGI magazines; Six (6) weld dimples with a horizontal line immediately above the bottom pair - CMI   Checkmate Industries.

Being that I purchased these so long ago, I had called Springfield Armory customer service to verify the manufacturer.  They stated all the magazines have been made by Check-Mate Industries(CMI) for the last 20 + years for springfield armory. The last few years they(springfield Armory) have stamped their logo on it. A few years back they also had some USGI surplus. 

Also, they reminded me you need to have the bolt locked back to insert the 5 round is what I believe he told me.

From Check-Mate's website
(M1A) M14 Magazines
Currently Check-Mate Industries is the largest (M1A) M14 magazines manufacturer for the United States Military. 
Check-Mate Industries is recognized as being America’s number one manufacturer of M14 magazines.
At present the only round capacity we offer for the M14 magazines are 5, 10 and 20 rounds. CMI is currently working on the development and production of a reliable 25rd M14 magazine.

http://www.checkmateindustries.com/handgun.htm#tbl5 This link will take you to the magazine section. They did allow direct sales. The SA customer service guy was nice enough to tell me their supplier and once he did, I remembered instantly that was who had produced them.
